flowRoot.flowPara: Domains of application for the demographic time framework
All work (LaTeX, R, etc) for this project is hosted in an open repository on github:
Check back there for paper updates! This work is still very much in progress.

The demographic time framework defines the time-space for birth-death processes that produce overlapping lifecourses. The framework is generally applicable to any domain where population-level variation occurs over time and within "life". Since the framework is an abstraction, both intuitively coherent, but not necessarily obvious to translate into applications, we here offer a potluck of suggested applications in a variety of domains, both within and outside demography. Application domains include subfields of human demography focusing on particular transitions, stages of the life course, or special sub populations (prisoners, athletes, and professors), but also applications to non-human species, natural phenomena, and artificial objects.
"T. Riffe, A. Lenart, V. Canudas-Romo "Distributional aspects of remaining years of life" (draft in progress)

flowRoot.flowPara: A set of events in calendar time, such as birth or death (or any arbitrary kind of transition) can be represented on a timeline. Durations are simply time differences between events, and more events imply more durations. Graphs provide a more compact representation of the relationship between events and durations, first where events are vertices and durations are edges, and second, where both events and durations are edges. This later kind of graph extends to the familiar geometry of the Lexis diagram.

flowRoot.flowPara: How many triangles can you count in these graphs? That's how many Lexis-style diagrams you could potentially derive and relate. Full diagram representations of systems with more than 3 events go beyond three dimensions. The demographic time framework has 3 events (birth, death, and period), and can be represented in three dimensions. That's fun, but you don't need it to do analyses.
